# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference

## 2.1 Broadcast Receiver — Internal Architecture

### Types of Broadcast Registration

1. **Static (Manifest-Declared) Receivers**
   - Declared inside the `<application>` tag of `AndroidManifest.xml` using `<receiver>`.
   - Survive application process death — the system can launch the app to deliver the broadcast.
   - Useful for high-priority system events (e.g., `BOOT_COMPLETED`, custom OEM push events).

2. **Dynamic (Context-Registered) Receivers**
   - Registered at runtime using `Context.registerReceiver()`.
   - Bound to the lifecycle of the registered object (e.g., Activity or Fragment).
   - Must be unregistered in `onPause()`/`onDestroy()` to prevent memory leaks.
   - Required in **Android 8.0 (API 26)+** for most implicit broadcasts (manifest declarations are largely ignored unless exempted).

### Broadcast Categories (Visibility Scope)

- **Normal Broadcasts** — Asynchronous; receivers run in an undefined order; cannot use result APIs.
- **System Broadcasts** — Sent only by the system (e.g., `ACTION_POWER_CONNECTED`).
- **Ordered Broadcasts** — Synchronous; delivered to one receiver at a time in priority order; receivers can abort or modify the result.
- **Sticky Broadcasts** *(Deprecated since API 21)* — Remain available after delivery for late registrants.
- **Local Broadcasts** — Scope limited to the application process via `LocalBroadcastManager` (deprecated; modern replacement is **Kotlin Flows / SharedFlow / AndroidX Lifecycle-aware components**).

### The `onReceive()` Lifecycle

The Android system invokes the single callback method:

```java
public void onReceive(Context context, Intent intent)
```

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Pitfall**: The `onReceive()` method runs on the **main thread** and has a **10-second execution limit** (since Android 8.0+ the foreground app allowance is reduced; receivers must complete quickly). Heavy work such as network calls or large DB writes should be delegated to a `WorkManager` job or `goAsync()` pattern (deprecated in API 34 — use `PendingResult` cautiously or push to a `Service`).

### Security Model

| Mechanism | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `android:exported="false"` | Restrict receiver to same-app calls |
| `android:permission` | Require sender to hold a permission |
| `Intent.setPackage()` / explicit `ComponentName` | Target a specific app, bypassing implicit broadcast |
| `RECEIVER_NOT_EXPORTED` flag (API 33+) | Mandatory for runtime registration of unexported receivers |
| `RECEIVER_EXPORTED` flag (API 33+) | Explicit opt-in for exported runtime receivers |

---

## 2.2 Content Provider — Internal Architecture

### Standard CRUD Interface

Every Content Provider implements the abstract class `ContentProvider` and overrides the following methods:

| Method | Purpose | Returns |
|---|---|---|
| `query()` | Read rows matching URI | `Cursor` |
| `insert()` | Insert a new row | `URI` of inserted row |
| `update()` | Update existing rows | `int` (rows affected) |
| `delete()` | Remove rows | `int` (rows affected) |
| `getType()` | Return MIME type for URI | `String` |
| `onCreate()` | Provider initialization | `boolean` |

### Content URI Anatomy

A Content URI is structured as:

`content://<authority>/<path>/<id>`

- **Scheme** — `content://` (mandatory)
- **Authority** — Unique provider identifier (typically `application_package_name.provider_name`)
- **Path** — Logical table or category
- **ID** — Optional specific row identifier (`#` wildcard for any ID, `*` for any string)

**Example**: `content://com.ktu.iotapp.provider/sensor_readings/42`
- Authority: `com.ktu.iotapp.provider`
- Path: `sensor_readings`
- ID: `42`

### `UriMatcher` Constants

| Pattern | Constant Type | Matches |
|---|---|---|
| `content://auth/sensor_readings` | `MATCH_ALL` (`/*`) | All rows |
| `content://auth/sensor_readings/#` | `MATCH_ID` (`/#`) | Single row by numeric ID |
| `content://auth/devices/*/config` | `MATCH_SUBPATH` | Subpath wildcard |

### Accessing a Provider (Client Side)

Clients use the singleton `ContentResolver` obtained via `context.getContentResolver()`. Operations:

```java
Cursor cursor = getContentResolver().query(
    Uri.parse("content://com.ktu.iotapp.provider/sensor_readings"),
    projection,     // columns
    selection,      // WHERE clause
    selectionArgs,  // WHERE arguments
    sortOrder       // ORDER BY
);
```

### Notification of Data Changes

Providers call `ContentResolver.notifyChange()` after mutations. Observers register with `ContentResolver.registerContentObserver()` to be notified — this is the **push-style update** mechanism that mimics broadcasts but is scoped to a specific URI.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU High-Yield Insight**: Content Observers + Content Providers form the architectural basis for live data sharing in IoT dashboards (e.g., a wearable's heart-rate data being live-streamed to a dashboard app).

---

## 2.3 High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### Broadcast Receiver — Essential Formulas / Templates

| Concept | Standard Form / Template |
|---|---|
| Manifest Declaration | `<receiver android:name=".MyReceiver" android:exported="true\|false" android:permission="com.ktu.PERMISSION"> <intent-filter> <action android:name="android.intent.action.BOOT_COMPLETED"/> </intent-filter> </receiver>` |
| Runtime Registration | `IntentFilter filter = new IntentFilter(ConnectivityManager.CONNECTIVITY_ACTION); registerReceiver(myReceiver, filter);` |
| Custom Broadcast Send | `Intent i = new Intent("com.ktu.iotapp.SENSOR_TRIGGER"); i.putExtra("deviceId", 42); sendBroadcast(i);` |
| Ordered Broadcast | `sendOrderedBroadcast(intent, receiverPermission, resultReceiver, scheduler, initialCode, initialData, initialExtras);` |
| Async Work | `final PendingResult pr = goAsync(); new Thread(() -> { /* work */ pr.finish(); }).start();` |

### Content Provider — Essential Formulas / Templates

| Concept | Standard Form / Template |
|---|---|
| Manifest Declaration | `<provider android:name=".SensorProvider" android:authorities="com.ktu.iotapp.provider" android:exported="false" android:grantUriPermissions="true"/>` |
| URI Matcher Code | `matcher.addURI("com.ktu.iotapp.provider", "sensor_readings", MATCH_ALL); matcher.addURI("com.ktu.iotapp.provider", "sensor_readings/#", MATCH_ID);` |
| MIME Type for Row | `return "vnd.android.cursor.item/vnd.com.ktu.iotapp.sensor_reading";` |
| MIME Type for All Rows | `return "vnd.android.cursor.dir/vnd.com.ktu.iotapp.sensor_reading";` |
| Notify Change | `getContext().getContentResolver().notifyChange(uri, null);` |
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations, Code Logic & Analytical Walkthroughs

## 3.1 Derivation: Designing a Broadcast Receiver for an IoT BLE Disconnection Event

**Problem Context**: Your IoT fitness band (a BLE peripheral) must notify the mobile app the moment it disconnects. Design the broadcast flow.

### Step 1 — Define the Custom Action Constant

```java
public final class IotActions {
    public static final String ACTION_BLE_DISCONNECTED =
        "com.ktu.iotapp.action.BLE_DISCONNECTED";
    public static final String EXTRA_DEVICE_ADDRESS = "device_address";
    public static final String EXTRA_TIMESTAMP      = "timestamp_ms";
}
```

*Logic*: We define a single source-of-truth action string. The static class prevents duplication and typo-bugs. The `EXTRA_*` keys are the payload contract.

### Step 2 — Declare the Receiver in the Manifest

```xml
<receiver
    android:name=".BleDisconnectReceiver"
    android:exported="false">
    <intent-filter>
        <action android:name="com.ktu.iotapp.action.BLE_DISCONNECTED" />
    </intent-filter>
</receiver>
```

*Logic*: `exported="false"` blocks external apps from spoofing a disconnection broadcast — critical for security in IoT. We also omit any `android:permission` since the broadcast is internal.

### Step 3 — Implement the Receiver Class

```java
public class BleDisconnectReceiver extends BroadcastReceiver {
    @Override
    public void onReceive(Context context, Intent intent) {
        if (!IotActions.ACTION_BLE_DISCONNECTED.equals(intent.getAction()))
            return;

        String address  = intent.getStringExtra(IotActions.EXTRA_DEVICE_ADDRESS);
        long   timestamp = intent.getLongExtra(IotActions.EXTRA_TIMESTAMP,
                                               System.currentTimeMillis());

        // Step 4: Persist to Content Provider
        ContentValues values = new ContentValues();
        values.put("device_address", address);
        values.put("event",          "DISCONNECT");
        values.put("timestamp_ms",   timestamp);
        context.getContentResolver()
               .insert(SensorContract.Disconnects.CONTENT_URI, values);

        // Step 5: Notify the user
        NotificationManager nm = (NotificationManager)
            context.getSystemService(Context.NOTIFICATION_SERVICE);
        Notification n = new NotificationCompat.Builder(context, "ble_channel")
            .setContentTitle("Band Disconnected")
            .setContentText("Device " + address + " is offline.")
            .setSmallIcon(android.R.drawable.stat_notify_error)
            .setAutoCancel(true)
            .build();
        nm.notify((int) timestamp, n);
    }
}
```

*Logic*: The receiver validates intent identity, extracts payload, writes to a Content Provider for persistence, and emits a user notification — all in one tight `onReceive()` cycle.

### Step 4 — Send the Broadcast from a BLE Service

```java
public class BleService extends Service {
    @Override
    public void onConnectionLost(BluetoothDevice device) {
        Intent i = new Intent(IotActions.ACTION_BLE_DISCONNECTED);
        i.setPackage(getPackageName());           // explicit target
        i.putExtra(IotActions.EXTRA_DEVICE_ADDRESS, device.getAddress());
        i.putExtra(IotActions.EXTRA_TIMESTAMP,     System.currentTimeMillis());
        sendBroadcast(i);
    }
}
```

*Logic*: `setPackage()` converts the broadcast into an explicit one — bypassing Android 8+ implicit broadcast restrictions and ensuring the OS doesn't filter it out.

---

## 3.2 Derivation: Building a Custom Content Provider for IoT Sensor Logs

### Step 1 — Define the Contract Class (Public API)

```java
public final class SensorContract {
    private SensorContract() {}

    public static final String AUTHORITY = "com.ktu.iotapp.provider";

    public static final class SensorReadings implements BaseColumns {
        public static final String PATH = "sensor_readings";
        public static final Uri CONTENT_URI =
            Uri.parse("content://" + AUTHORITY + "/" + PATH);

        public static final String COL_DEVICE_ID = "device_id";
        public static final String COL_TYPE      = "sensor_type";
        public static final String COL_VALUE     = "value";
        public static final String COL_TIMESTAMP = "timestamp_ms";
    }
}
```

*Logic*: The `Contract` class centralizes URI and column names. Other components depend on this contract, **not** on the provider class — enabling clean separation of concerns.

### Step 2 — Implement the Provider's `onCreate()` and URI Matcher

```java
public class SensorProvider extends ContentProvider {
    private static final int MATCH_READINGS    = 100;
    private static final int MATCH_READING_ID  = 101;

    private static final UriMatcher sUriMatcher = new UriMatcher(
        UriMatcher.NO_MATCH);
    static {
        sUriMatcher.addURI(SensorContract.AUTHORITY,
                           SensorContract.SensorReadings.PATH,
                           MATCH_READINGS);
        sUriMatcher.addURI(SensorContract.AUTHORITY,
                           SensorContract.SensorReadings.PATH + "/#",
                           MATCH_READING_ID);
    }

    private SensorDbHelper mDbHelper;

    @Override
    public boolean onCreate() {
        mDbHelper = new SensorDbHelper(getContext());
        return true;
    }
}
```

*Logic*: The `UriMatcher` is initialized once in a static block to avoid object recreation. Each constant uniquely maps a URI pattern — this is the **dispatch mechanism** for incoming queries.

### Step 3 — Implement `query()` with Branched Logic

```java
@Override
public Cursor query(Uri uri, String[] projection, String selection,
                    String[] selectionArgs, String sortOrder) {
    SQLiteDatabase db = mDbHelper.getReadableDatabase();
    SQLiteQueryBuilder qb = new SQLiteQueryBuilder();
    qb.setTables(SensorDbHelper.TABLE_SENSOR_READINGS);

    int match = sUriMatcher.match(uri);
    switch (match) {
        case MATCH_READINGS:
            // No filter — return all rows
            break;
        case MATCH_READING_ID:
            long id = ContentUris.parseId(uri);
            qb.appendWhere(SensorContract.SensorReadings._ID + "=" + id);
            break;
        default:
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Unknown URI: " + uri);
    }

    Cursor cursor = qb.query(db, projection, selection, selectionArgs,
                             null, null, sortOrder);
    cursor.setNotificationUri(getContext().getContentResolver(), uri);
    return cursor;
}
```

*Logic*: We use `SQLiteQueryBuilder` to defend against SQL injection by allowing only pre-defined tables. `setNotificationUri` registers the cursor to receive change notifications from `notifyChange()`.

### Step 4 — Implement Insert with Auto-Notify

```java
@Override
public Uri insert(Uri uri, ContentValues values) {
    if (sUriMatcher.match(uri) != MATCH_READINGS)
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Insert requires dir URI");

    SQLiteDatabase db = mDbHelper.getWritableDatabase();
    long id = db.insert(SensorDbHelper.TABLE_SENSOR_READINGS,
                        null, values);
    if (id > 0) {
        Uri newUri = ContentUris.withAppendedId(
            SensorContract.SensorReadings.CONTENT_URI, id);
        getContext().getContentResolver().notifyChange(uri, null);
        return newUri;
    }
    throw new SQLiteException("Insert failed: " + uri);
}
```

*Logic*: Inserts are only allowed against the directory URI. The auto-generated row ID is appended to the base URI to construct a unique item URI. `notifyChange()` triggers any registered `ContentObserver`s.

### Step 5 — Mathematical Formulation of Provider Throughput (Conceptual)

For an IoT sensor provider ingesting readings from $N$ sensors at rate $r_i$ (samples/sec) each:

$$R_{\text{total}} = \sum_{i=1}^{N} r_i \quad \text{[samples/sec]}$$

The average database write latency $L_w$ must satisfy:

$$L_w \;\le\; \frac{1}{R_{\text{total}}}$$

Otherwise, the write queue grows unboundedly and triggers `SQLiteException`. For the KTU 2024 scheme, this relation illustrates the **real-time constraint** of an IoT Content Provider and is a high-yield exam concept.

---

## 3.3 Analytical Matrix: When to Use What?

| Scenario | Recommended Component | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| React to Wi-Fi state change | Broadcast Receiver (dynamic) | System event, one-shot |
| Persist BLE sensor history | Content Provider | Cross-app queryable, observable |
| Trigger a background task on boot | Broadcast Receiver + WorkManager | Decouples event from execution |
| Share config with a settings app | Content Provider + `grantUriPermissions` | Targeted, revocable access |
| Alert user on low battery | Broadcast Receiver (manifest) | Must fire even if app dead |
| Live-stream sensor data to UI | Content Provider + ContentObserver | Real-time, scoped notifications |
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

