# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

---

## Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 `[KTU University Exam – May 2024]`
**Differentiate between static and dynamic Broadcast Receivers. State the Android version where manifest-declared implicit receivers were largely restricted.**

**Model Answer**:
A *static receiver* is declared in `AndroidManifest.xml` using the `<receiver>` tag. It is registered at install time and can be invoked by the system **even when the application is not running**, by cold-starting the process. A *dynamic receiver* is registered at runtime via `Context.registerReceiver()` and is bound to the lifecycle of the registering component (Activity/Fragment). It **must be unregistered** to prevent memory leaks and is **not** invoked if the app process is dead.

Starting from **Android 8.0 (API level 26)**, the OS largely restricts manifest-declared receivers from receiving **implicit** broadcasts (e.g., `CONNECTIVITY_CHANGE`), although a small exempt list (boot, package install, locked boot, etc.) persists. From **Android 14 (API 34)**, runtime-registered receivers **must** explicitly declare `RECEIVER_EXPORTED` or `RECEIVER_NOT_EXPORTED` flags.

---

### Question 2 `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]`
**What is a Content Provider? Explain the structure of a Content URI with a suitable example for an IoT sensor data provider.**

**Model Answer**:
A Content Provider is an Android component that **manages access to structured data** and allows secure data sharing between applications, respecting Android's sandbox model. It exposes a CRUD interface (`query`, `insert`, `update`, `delete`, `getType`) accessed via the `ContentResolver` class.

**Content URI Structure**: `content://<authority>/<path>/<id>`

**Example**: `content://com.ktu.iotapp.provider/sensor_readings/42`

- `content://` — URI scheme indicating a Content Provider
- `com.ktu.iotapp.provider` — authority (unique provider name)
- `sensor_readings` — logical path (table name)
- `42` — specific row ID (optional)

Clients query this URI to retrieve the 42nd sensor reading from the IoT app's database.

---

## Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each)

> [!NOTE]
> As per KTU 2024 ESE guidelines, Module 1 internal choice is provided below. **Answer EITHER Question A OR Question B.**

---

### Question A `[KTU University Exam – June 2024]` — 14 Marks

**(a)** With a neat diagram, explain the architecture and lifecycle of an Android Broadcast Receiver. Discuss the significance of ordered broadcasts. *(7 Marks)*

**(b)** Design and explain a Broadcast Receiver for an IoT home automation app that listens for a `MOTION_DETECTED` custom broadcast and toggles a smart light. Provide the manifest declaration, the receiver class, and the broadcast-sender code. *(7 Marks)*

#### Model Solution

**Part (a) — Architecture & Lifecycle (7 Marks)**:

The Broadcast Receiver architecture has three actors:
1. **Sender** — Issues an `Intent` via `sendBroadcast()`, `sendOrderedBroadcast()`, or `sendStickyBroadcast()` (deprecated).
2. **ActivityManagerService (AMS)** — The system service that **intercepts** the intent and dispatches it to matching receivers.
3. **Receiver** — Implements `BroadcastReceiver.onReceive(Context, Intent)`.

**Lifecycle**:
- Receiver exists as a Java object whose `onReceive()` is invoked by AMS.
- During `onReceive()`, the receiver is considered **active**; if it returns within **10 seconds**, AMS releases the process handle.
- If `goAsync()` is called, the receiver gets a `PendingResult` and can perform async work for up to **10 seconds** before calling `finish()`.
- After the receiver returns, the Android system may **kill the process at any time** if other components don't need it.

**Ordered Broadcasts**:
- Receivers are notified **one at a time** in **descending priority order** (set via `android:priority` or `IntentFilter.setPriority()`).
- The initial result can be modified by each receiver.
- Any receiver can call `abortBroadcast()` to **terminate** the chain — useful for permission-style filtering.
- The `resultReceiver` (a special final receiver) is invoked last with the final result code, data, and extras.
- Significance: enables **chained processing pipelines** (e.g., spam-filter → logger → final UI handler).

**Part (b) — IoT Motion Detector Receiver (7 Marks)**:

**Manifest Declaration**:
```xml
<receiver
    android:name=".MotionLightReceiver"
    android:exported="false">
    <intent-filter android:priority="10">
        <action android:name="com.ktu.iotapp.action.MOTION_DETECTED" />
    </intent-filter>
</receiver>
```

**Receiver Class**:
```java
public class MotionLightReceiver extends BroadcastReceiver {
    @Override
    public void onReceive(Context ctx, Intent intent) {
        if (!"com.ktu.iotapp.action.MOTION_DETECTED".equals(intent.getAction()))
            return;
        boolean motion = intent.getBooleanExtra("motion", false);
        long timestamp  = intent.getLongExtra("timestamp",
                                              System.currentTimeMillis());
        // 1. Toggle smart light via IoT hub
        LightController.toggle(intent.getStringExtra("lightId"), motion);
        // 2. Log event to Content Provider
        ContentValues v = new ContentValues();
        v.put("event_type", "MOTION");
        v.put("motion_state", motion);
        v.put("timestamp", timestamp);
        ctx.getContentResolver().insert(
            SensorContract.Events.CONTENT_URI, v);
    }
}
```

**Sender Code (from PIR sensor Service)**:
```java
Intent i = new Intent("com.ktu.iotapp.action.MOTION_DETECTED");
i.setPackage(getPackageName());    // explicit broadcast
i.putExtra("motion",    true);
i.putExtra("lightId",   "LIVING_ROOM_01");
i.putExtra("timestamp", System.currentTimeMillis());
sendBroadcast(i);
```

**Validation**:
- The receiver uses `setPackage()` to avoid Android 8+ implicit broadcast restrictions.
- Cross-references Content Provider for persistent logging.
- Uses an explicit action string to prevent collision with system actions.

