# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 The Android Event Dispatch Pipeline

The end-to-end flow of a single user interaction follows a strict sequence enforced by the Android Window Manager:

1. **Touch Capture**: The system captures raw touch coordinates from the input device driver at the **kernel layer**.
2. **MotionEvent Generation**: The `InputDispatcher` wraps these coordinates into a `MotionEvent` object.
3. **Event Queue Insertion**: The event is placed in the **Main Looper's MessageQueue**.
4. **ViewRoot Dispatch**: `ViewRootImpl` receives the event and traverses the **View Hierarchy** in a top-down manner.
5. **Hit Testing**: Each `ViewGroup` performs `dispatchTouchEvent()` to determine if coordinates lie within its bounds (and not blocked by a child).
6. **Listener Invocation**: The matching `Listener.onEvent()` method is invoked on the **Main (UI) Thread**.
7. **Handler Execution**: The overridden callback executes the user-defined logic.

> [!TIP]
> **Why must UI events run on the Main Thread?** Android requires all View manipulation to occur on the thread that owns the View. Performing event handling on a background thread results in `CalledFromWrongThreadException`.

## 2.2 The Three Programming Models for Handling Clicks

### Model 1 — Activity Implements the Listener Interface (Declarative Binding)

The Activity class declaration includes `implements View.OnClickListener`. A single `onClick(View v)` method then handles events for multiple views by switching on the view ID using `v.getId()`.

### Model 2 — Anonymous Inner Class (Event-Specific Binding)

A dedicated listener is attached inline at the point of widget creation, ideal when only **one widget** needs the handler. This is the **most common pattern in KTU lab exams**.

### Model 3 — XML Attribute (`android:onClick`)

The layout XML specifies `android:onClick="methodName"`. The Activity must expose a public method matching the signature `public void methodName(View view)`. This model is restricted to **`View.OnClickListener`-compatible events only** and is unavailable for `TextWatcher`, `OnCheckedChangeListener`, etc.

## 2.3 KTU Cheat Sheet — Listener Interface Reference

| Listener Interface | Callback Signature | Trigger Condition |
|---|---|---|
| `View.OnClickListener` | `void onClick(View v)` | Quick release of a tap inside view bounds (**~500ms**) |
| `View.OnLongClickListener` | `boolean onLongClick(View v)` | Press held for **500ms+**; return `true` to consume |
| `CompoundButton.OnCheckedChangeListener` | `void onCheckedChanged(CompoundButton b, boolean isChecked)` | Toggleable widget state flip |
| `SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener` | `void onProgressChanged(SeekBar s, int p, boolean fromUser)` | Slider drag or programmatic set |
| `SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener` | `void onStartTrackingTouch(SeekBar s)` | User begins dragging |
| `SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener` | `void onStopTrackingTouch(SeekBar s)` | User releases slider |
| `AdapterView.OnItemSelectedListener` | `void onItemSelected(AdapterView<?> p, View v, int pos, long id)` | Spinner/ListView item picked |
| `AdapterView.OnItemSelectedListener` | `void onNothingSelected(AdapterView<?> p)` | Adapter becomes empty |
| `TextWatcher` | `void beforeTextChanged(...)` | Character insertion imminent |
| `TextWatcher` | `void onTextChanged(...)` | Characters changed in field |
| `TextWatcher` | `void afterTextChanged(Editable s)` | Field state finalized |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Engineering Utility**: Event listeners are the backbone of **IoT control dashboards**. A mobile app controlling a smart light bulb uses `OnClickListener` to toggle the bulb, `SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener` to adjust brightness, and `OnCheckedChangeListener` for automated schedules.

