## 3.1 Handling a Button Click — Anonymous Inner Class Approach

This is the canonical "Hello World" of Android interactivity and is a **guaranteed KTU lab question**.

### Step 1 — XML Layout Definition

```xml
<!-- res/layout/activity_main.xml -->
<LinearLayout
    xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:orientation="vertical"
    android:padding="16dp">

    <TextView
        android:id="@+id/tvCounter"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:text="Clicks: 0"
        android:textSize="22sp" />

    <Button
        android:id="@+id/btnIncrement"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:text="Increment Counter" />
</LinearLayout>
```

### Step 2 — Activity Java Code with Listener Registration

```java
// MainActivity.java
import android.os.Bundle;
import android.view.View;
import android.widget.Button;
import android.widget.TextView;
import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity;

public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    private TextView tvCounter;
    private Button btnIncrement;
    private int counter = 0;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

        // Step A: Obtain references to inflated views using findViewById
        tvCounter   = findViewById(R.id.tvCounter);
        btnIncrement = findViewById(R.id.btnIncrement);

        // Step B: Register the listener via anonymous inner class
        btnIncrement.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
            @Override
            public void onClick(View v) {
                // Step C: Business logic executed on UI thread
                counter++;
                tvCounter.setText("Clicks: " + counter);
            }
        });
    }
}
```

**Explanation of Execution:**
1. `setContentView()` inflates the XML layout into the View hierarchy.
2. `findViewById()` performs a **Depth-First Search** on the hierarchy, returning a typed reference.
3. `setOnClickListener()` stores the listener inside the View's internal `ListenerInfo` mListener field.
4. When the user taps, the framework invokes `mListener.onClick(this)`, executing the counter logic.

## 3.2 Handling a SeekBar Change — Brightness Slider for IoT Lamp

The `SeekBar` emits three distinct events during a single drag. The handler must track all three to know when a value is "committed" — useful when syncing brightness to a real bulb only after the user stops adjusting.

```java
import android.widget.SeekBar;

SeekBar seekBrightness = findViewById(R.id.seekBrightness);
seekBrightness.setMax(100);   // 0% to 100%

seekBrightness.setOnSeekBarChangeListener(new SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener() {
    @Override
    public void onProgressChanged(SeekBar seekBar, int progress, boolean fromUser) {
        // Fires repeatedly while dragging — used for live UI feedback
        tvLivePreview.setText("Brightness: " + progress + "%");
    }

    @Override
    public void onStartTrackingTouch(SeekBar seekBar) {
        // Suppress cloud transmission until user releases
        isUserDragging = true;
    }

    @Override
    public void onStopTrackingTouch(SeekBar seekBar) {
        // Commit final value to IoT device here
        int finalValue = seekBar.getProgress();
        mqttClient.publish("home/lamp/brightness", finalValue);
        isUserDragging = false;
    }
});
```

## 3.3 Handling EditText Text Changes — Search Filter with TextWatcher

Unlike click listeners, text-change events require implementing **three methods** of the `TextWatcher` interface. This is the only listener in this module where you implement multiple methods.

```java
import android.text.Editable;
import android.text.TextWatcher;
import android.widget.EditText;
import android.widget.ArrayAdapter;
import android.widget.ListView;

EditText etSearch = findViewById(R.id.etSearch);
ListView lvDevices = findViewById(R.id.lvDevices);

etSearch.addTextChangedListener(new TextWatcher() {
    @Override
    public void beforeTextChanged(CharSequence s, int start, int count, int after) {
        // Invoked BEFORE characters are inserted/deleted
    }

    @Override
    public void onTextChanged(CharSequence s, int start, int before, int count) {
        // Invoked as characters change — filter the list here
        String query = s.toString().toLowerCase();
        adapter.getFilter().filter(query);
    }

    @Override
    public void afterTextChanged(Editable s) {
        // Invoked AFTER the change is committed to the Editable buffer
    }
});
```

> [!NOTE]
> The `onTextChanged()` and `afterTextChanged()` callbacks fire **on every keystroke**. For expensive operations (e.g., network search), debounce the calls using a `Handler.postDelayed()` to avoid spamming the backend.

## 3.4 Mathematical Trace — Event Propagation Coordinates

When the user touches coordinate $(x, y)$ on a device with screen resolution $W \times H$, the framework performs a hit-test against every visible View. The decision logic can be abstracted as:

$$
\text{hit}(V) = 
\begin{cases}
\text{true} & \text{if } x \in [V.\text{left},\ V.\text{right}] \ \land\ y \in [V.\text{top},\ V.\text{bottom}] \\
\text{false} & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

The final dispatch target $V_{\text{target}}$ is the **deepest (leaf) View** in the hierarchy whose bounding box satisfies `hit(V) = true`. The event is then routed to the **topmost registered listener** $L_{\text{top}}$ attached to $V_{\text{target}}$.

$$
V_{\text{target}} = \arg\max_{V \in \text{Hierarchy}} \left\{ \text{depth}(V) \;\middle|\; \text{hit}(V) = \text{true} \right\}
$$

$$
L_{\text{top}} = \text{peek}\Big(\text{Listeners}\big(V_{\text{target}}\big)\Big)
$$

$$
\text{Callback Invoked} \rightarrow L_{\text{top}}.\text{onEvent}\big(V_{\text{target}}, \text{eventData}\big)
$$

If $L_{\text{top}}$.onEvent returns `false` (only applicable to `OnLongClickListener` and `OnTouchListener`), the event **bubbles up** to the parent ViewGroup, allowing parent containers to react if the child did not consume it.

