## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question 1 `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2023]`

**Explain the role of an Event Listener in Android. Differentiate between `OnClickListener` and `OnLongClickListener`.**

**Model Answer:**

An **Event Listener** in Android is a Java/Kotlin interface defined in the `android.view` package that contains one or more **callback methods**. These callbacks are invoked by the Android Framework whenever a corresponding user interaction occurs on a View to which the listener has been registered. The listener acts as a contract — the View promises to notify the implementation whenever a specific event happens.

**Differences:**

| Parameter | `OnClickListener` | `OnLongClickListener` |
|---|---|---|
| **Trigger** | Quick tap release | Press held for **~500 ms** |
| **Return type** | `void` | `boolean` (return `true` to consume) |
| **Method** | `onClick(View v)` | `onLongClick(View v)` |
| **Use case** | Normal button actions | Context menus, drag handles |
| **Multiple triggers** | Fires once per tap | Can suppress subsequent click if `true` returned |

The `OnLongClickListener` returning `true` indicates the event has been consumed, preventing the subsequent `onClick` from firing for the same gesture.

---

### Question 2 `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**What is the purpose of the `TextWatcher` interface? List its three callback methods with their signatures.**

**Model Answer:**

The `TextWatcher` interface is used to **observe and react to changes in the text content of an `EditText` (or its subclasses)**. It is essential for implementing features like live search filters, input validators, character counters, and dynamic UI updates.

Unlike most listeners, `TextWatcher` requires implementation of **three methods**:

1. `void beforeTextChanged(CharSequence s, int start, int count, int after)` — invoked immediately **before** the text buffer is modified.
2. `void onTextChanged(CharSequence s, int start, int before, int count)` — invoked **during** the change to inform about the characters being inserted/deleted.
3. `void afterTextChanged(Editable s)` — invoked **after** the text change has been committed to the buffer; the final state can be retrieved via `s.toString()`.

The listener is attached using `editText.addTextChangedListener(textWatcherInstance)`.

