### Question A `[KTU University Exam - Dec 2024]`

**(a)** Explain the three different approaches to handling click events on a `Button` in Android, with suitable code snippets. Compare their advantages and disadvantages. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Answer:**

Android provides **three distinct programming models** for registering click event handlers:

**Approach 1 — Activity Implements `View.OnClickListener`**

```java
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity 
                            implements View.OnClickListener {
    private Button btnRed, btnGreen;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);
        btnRed   = findViewById(R.id.btnRed);
        btnGreen = findViewById(R.id.btnGreen);
        btnRed.setOnClickListener(this);
        btnGreen.setOnClickListener(this);
    }

    @Override
    public void onClick(View v) {
        int id = v.getId();
        if (id == R.id.btnRed)   { /* handle red */ }
        else if (id == R.id.btnGreen) { /* handle green */ }
    }
}
```

*Advantages:* Centralized logic; reduces anonymous class boilerplate.
*Disadvantages:* Requires `if-else`/`switch` branching; less readable for many buttons.

**Approach 2 — Anonymous Inner Class**

```java
btnRed.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    @Override
    public void onClick(View v) {
        // Inline logic
    }
});
```

*Advantages:* Logic is co-located with the widget setup; highly readable.
*Disadvantages:* Creates a new class instance per widget; memory leak risk if Activity reference is held.

**Approach 3 — XML `android:onClick` Attribute**

```xml
<Button android:id="@+id/btnRed"
        android:onClick="handleRedClick"
        android:text="Red" />
```

```java
public void handleRedClick(View view) {
    // Framework invokes this method automatically
}
```

*Advantages:* Zero Java code for listener wiring; clean separation of UI from logic.
*Disadvantages:* Limited to `onClick`-style events; method must be `public void (View)`; no compile-time check on method name.

