**(b)** With a neat diagram and code, explain how you would implement a brightness control feature using `SeekBar` for an IoT smart lamp application. Discuss the difference between `onProgressChanged`, `onStartTrackingTouch`, and `onStopTrackingTouch`. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Answer:**

**Conceptual Design:**
A `SeekBar` widget in the Android UI acts as the slider. As the user drags, the app must (i) provide live on-screen feedback of the brightness value, and (ii) transmit the final value to the IoT lamp only when the user stops dragging, to avoid flooding the network.

**Layout — `activity_brightness.xml`:**

```xml
<LinearLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:orientation="vertical"
    android:padding="20dp">

    <TextView
        android:id="@+id/tvBrightnessLabel"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:text="Brightness: 0%"
        android:textSize="20sp" />

    <SeekBar
        android:id="@+id/seekBrightness"
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:max="100"
        android:progress="0" />
</LinearLayout>
```

**Activity Code:**

```java
public class BrightnessActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    private TextView tvBrightnessLabel;
    private SeekBar seekBrightness;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_brightness);

        tvBrightnessLabel = findViewById(R.id.tvBrightnessLabel);
        seekBrightness    = findViewById(R.id.seekBrightness);

        seekBrightness.setOnSeekBarChangeListener(new SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener() {
            @Override
            public void onProgressChanged(SeekBar seekBar, int progress, boolean fromUser) {
                tvBrightnessLabel.setText("Brightness: " + progress + "%");
            }

            @Override
            public void onStartTrackingTouch(SeekBar seekBar) {
                // User has begun dragging - log start time
            }

            @Override
            public void onStopTrackingTouch(SeekBar seekBar) {
                int finalBrightness = seekBar.getProgress();
                // Transmit to IoT device via MQTT/HTTP
                sendToLamp(finalBrightness);
            }
        });
    }

    private void sendToLamp(int brightness) {
        // MQTT publish or HTTP POST call here
    }
}
```

**Callback Differences:**

| Callback | Fires When | Typical Use |
|---|---|---|
| `onProgressChanged` | Continuously while dragging (multiple times per second) | Live UI label updates, visual feedback |
| `onStartTrackingTouch` | Once when finger first touches the thumb | Begin animation, pause auto-sync |
| `onStopTrackingTouch` | Once when finger lifts off the thumb | **Commit final value** to backend/IoT |

> [!WARNING]
> **Examiner's Pitfall — Part (b)**: A common mistake is publishing the brightness to the MQTT broker on every `onProgressChanged` call. This generates dozens of network packets per second and can crash the broker. Always debounce or commit only on `onStopTrackingTouch`.

