### Question B `[KTU University Exam - May 2024]`

**(a)** Illustrate the Android Event Dispatch mechanism with a flow diagram. Explain how the framework decides which View receives a particular `MotionEvent`. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Answer:**

**Android Event Dispatch Flow:**

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["User Touch at x,y on Screen"] --> B["Window Manager captures MotionEvent"]
    B --> C["Activity.dispatchTouchEvent"]
    C --> D["ViewGroup.dispatchTouchEvent"]
    D --> E{"Intercept Requested?"}
    E -->|Yes intercept true| F["Parent consumes onTouchEvent"]
    E -->|No| G["Iterate Children in Reverse Z Order"]
    G --> H{"Child Visible and hit true?"}
    H -->|Yes| I["Recursive dispatch to child"]
    H -->|No| G
    I --> J{"Child Listener returns true?"}
    J -->|Yes| K["Event consumed by child"]
    J -->|No| L["Return to parent onTouchEvent"]
```

**Decision Process:**

1. The **Activity** receives the `MotionEvent` first via `dispatchTouchEvent()`.
2. It forwards the event to the **root ViewGroup** (typically a `DecorView`).
3. The ViewGroup performs the **hit test**: it iterates through its children in **reverse drawing order** (last drawn = on top) and checks if $(x, y)$ falls within each child's bounds.
4. The **deepest child** whose bounds contain the point becomes the event target.
5. If the child has registered a listener (e.g., `OnClickListener`, `OnTouchListener`), the framework invokes it on the **Main UI Thread**.
6. Returning `true` from any callback **consumes** the event; returning `false` allows it to **bubble up** to the parent.

The **Z-order** is determined by the sequence in which children are added to the parent layout. Children added later appear on top and receive events first.

