**(b)** Write an Android program to implement a search filter that dynamically updates a `ListView` as the user types into an `EditText`. Explain the role of `TextWatcher`. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Answer:**

**Layout — `activity_search.xml`:**

```xml
<LinearLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:orientation="vertical"
    android:padding="10dp">

    <EditText
        android:id="@+id/etSearch"
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:hint="Search devices..."
        android:inputType="text" />

    <ListView
        android:id="@+id/lvDevices"
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="match_parent" />
</LinearLayout>
```

**Activity Code:**

```java
import android.text.Editable;
import android.text.TextWatcher;
import android.widget.ArrayAdapter;
import android.widget.EditText;
import android.widget.ListView;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;

public class SearchActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    private EditText etSearch;
    private ListView lvDevices;
    private ArrayAdapter<String> adapter;
    private final List<String> masterList = Arrays.asList(
        "Smart Bulb", "Smart Plug", "Temperature Sensor", "Motion Sensor",
        "Door Lock", "Camera", "Smoke Detector", "Humidity Sensor"
    );

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_search);

        etSearch = findViewById(R.id.etSearch);
        lvDevices = findViewById(R.id.lvDevices);

        adapter = new ArrayAdapter<>(this,
                                     android.R.layout.simple_list_item_1,
                                     new ArrayList<>(masterList));
        lvDevices.setAdapter(adapter);

        etSearch.addTextChangedListener(new TextWatcher() {
            @Override
            public void beforeTextChanged(CharSequence s, int start, int count, int after) {
                // No action required pre-change
            }

            @Override
            public void onTextChanged(CharSequence s, int start, int before, int count) {
                String query = s.toString().toLowerCase().trim();
                List<String> filtered = new ArrayList<>();
                for (String device : masterList) {
                    if (device.toLowerCase().contains(query)) {
                        filtered.add(device);
                    }
                }
                adapter.clear();
                adapter.addAll(filtered);
                adapter.notifyDataSetChanged();
            }

            @Override
            public void afterTextChanged(Editable s) {
                // Post-commit hook - can be used for analytics or error highlighting
            }
        });
    }
}
```

**Role of `TextWatcher`:**
The `TextWatcher` interface enables the application to **observe the lifecycle of text input** in real-time. It provides three distinct hooks (`beforeTextChanged`, `onTextChanged`, `afterTextChanged`) that fire at different stages of the edit, allowing developers to implement live filtering, validation, formatting (e.g., automatic credit-card spacing), and undo/redo logic. Without `TextWatcher`, the app would need to poll the `EditText` continuously, which is computationally wasteful and unresponsive.

> [!WARNING]
> **Examiner's Pitfall — Part B**: Students often forget to call `adapter.notifyDataSetChanged()` after modifying the data list. Without it, the `ListView` will not refresh visually even though the underlying data has changed. Marks are deducted specifically for this oversight.

