## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Event Handling** is the bridge between user gesture and app logic in Android.
- The four pillars are: **Event Source → Event → Listener → Handler (Callback)**.
- Three listener registration models: **Activity implements**, **Anonymous Inner Class**, **XML `android:onClick`** (last one is click-only).
- **`OnClickListener`** triggers on quick tap; **`OnLongClickListener`** triggers after **500 ms hold** and returns `boolean`.
- **`CompoundButton.OnCheckedChangeListener`** handles `CheckBox`, `RadioButton`, `Switch`, and `ToggleButton` state changes.
- **`SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener`** has **three methods**: `onProgressChanged` (live), `onStartTrackingTouch` (begin), `onStopTrackingTouch` (commit).
- **`TextWatcher`** is the only listener with **three mandatory callbacks**: `beforeTextChanged`, `onTextChanged`, `afterTextChanged`.
- **`AdapterView.OnItemSelectedListener`** has `onItemSelected` and `onNothingSelected`.
- All event callbacks execute on the **Main UI Thread**; long operations must be offloaded to background threads.
- The deepest View in the **Z-order** that passes the hit test becomes the event target.
- Returning `true` from `onTouchEvent` or `onLongClick` **consumes** the event, preventing parent bubbling.
- For IoT applications, **debounce** `onProgressChanged` events before network transmission to avoid backend overload.
- Always call `adapter.notifyDataSetChanged()` after modifying list data; otherwise the UI will not reflect updates.
- Forgetting `addTextChangedListener` registration is the **#1 mistake** in KTU TextWatcher questions.

