## 3.1 Walkthrough A — Passing Primitive & String Data (Activity → Activity)

### 3.1.1 The Scenario

A `LoginActivity` collects username/password, authenticates against a local mock, and passes the authenticated `username` and `userId` to `DashboardActivity`.

### 3.1.2 Step 1 — Sender Activity (Sending Side)

**File: `LoginActivity.java`**

```java
package com.ktu.iotapp;

import android.content.Intent;
import android.os.Bundle;
import android.widget.Button;
import android.widget.EditText;
import android.widget.Toast;
import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity;

public class LoginActivity extends AppCompatActivity {

    private EditText etUsername, etPassword;
    private Button btnLogin;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_login);

        etUsername = findViewById(R.id.etUsername);
        etPassword = findViewById(R.id.etPassword);
        btnLogin   = findViewById(R.id.btnLogin);

        btnLogin.setOnClickListener(v -> authenticate());
    }

    private void authenticate() {
        String username = etUsername.getText().toString().trim();
        String password = etPassword.getText().toString().trim();

        if (username.isEmpty() || password.isEmpty()) {
            Toast.makeText(this, "Fields cannot be empty", Toast.LENGTH_SHORT).show();
            return;
        }

        // === STEP 1: Create the Intent (the "envelope") ===
        // Explicit Intent: target component is named directly.
        Intent intent = new Intent(LoginActivity.this, DashboardActivity.class);

        // === STEP 2: Attach data via putExtra() (the "documents") ===
        // The method returns the same Intent, enabling fluent chaining.
        intent.putExtra("EXTRA_USERNAME", username);   // String
        intent.putExtra("EXTRA_USER_ID", 101);         // int
        intent.putExtra("EXTRA_IS_ADMIN", false);      // boolean
        intent.putExtra("EXTRA_LOGIN_TIME", System.currentTimeMillis()); // long

        // === STEP 3: Dispatch the Intent ===
        startActivity(intent);
    }
}
```

### 3.1.3 Step 2 — Receiver Activity (Receiving Side)

**File: `DashboardActivity.java`**

```java
package com.ktu.iotapp;

import android.content.Intent;
import android.os.Bundle;
import android.widget.TextView;
import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity;

public class DashboardActivity extends AppCompatActivity {

    private TextView tvWelcome;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_dashboard);

        tvWelcome = findViewById(R.id.tvWelcome);

        // === STEP 4: Retrieve the Intent that launched this Activity ===
        Intent incomingIntent = getIntent();

        // === STEP 5: Extract extras using type-safe getters ===
        // The second argument is the DEFAULT VALUE if the key is missing.
        String username = incomingIntent.getStringExtra("EXTRA_USERNAME");
        int userId      = incomingIntent.getIntExtra("EXTRA_USER_ID", -1);
        boolean isAdmin = incomingIntent.getBooleanExtra("EXTRA_IS_ADMIN", false);
        long loginTime  = incomingIntent.getLongExtra("EXTRA_LOGIN_TIME", 0L);

        // === STEP 6: Use the data ===
        if (username != null) {
            tvWelcome.setText("Welcome, " + username + " (ID: " + userId + ")");
        }
    }
}
```

### 3.1.4 Step-by-Step Logic Explanation (For Theory Answers)

| Step | Code Line | What the Android Framework Does |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `new Intent(LoginActivity.this, DashboardActivity.class)` | Allocates a new `Intent` object. Stores the source context and target component name. Sets `mComponent` field. |
| 2 | `intent.putExtra("EXTRA_USERNAME", username)` | Lazy-initializes the internal `mExtras` Bundle (if not yet created) and inserts the `(String key, String value)` pair. Returns `this` for chaining. |
| 3 | `startActivity(intent)` | Marshals the entire Intent (including extras Bundle) into a `Parcel`. Triggers Binder IPC to `ActivityManagerService` (system_server process). AMS resolves the target and launches `DashboardActivity` in a new task/affinity. |
| 4 | `getIntent()` in `DashboardActivity` | Returns the *unmarshalled* Intent object that AMS forwarded to the new activity. |
| 5 | `getStringExtra("EXTRA_USERNAME")` | Performs a `Bundle.getString()` lookup. Returns `null` if key not found. |
| 6 | UI update | Developer-controlled logic — Intent has done its job at this point. |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Conceptual Q:** *"What happens internally when you call `startActivity(intent)`?"*
> **Model Answer:** The ActivityManager receives the intent, parses the component name, verifies the target is declared in the manifest, starts the target activity's process if not already alive, instantiates the activity via reflection on `<application>` and `<activity>` tags, and delivers the intent to the new activity's `onCreate()` as the `savedInstanceState` argument's sibling. The system *serializes* the intent's `mExtras` Bundle into a `Parcel` for Binder IPC.

