## 3.2 Walkthrough B — Passing a Custom Object (Parcelable)

### 3.2.1 The IoT Scenario

A `Sensor` model class carries `id`, `name`, `type`, and `currentValue`. A list of `Sensor` objects must be passed from `DeviceListActivity` to `SensorControlActivity` for batch configuration.

### 3.2.2 Step 1 — Define the Parcelable Model

**File: `Sensor.java`**

```java
package com.ktu.iotapp.model;

import android.os.Parcel;
import android.os.Parcelable;
import androidx.annotation.NonNull;

public class Sensor implements Parcelable {

    // === Data fields ===
    private int id;
    private String name;
    private String type;          // e.g., "DHT22", "MQ-135"
    private float currentValue;
    private boolean isActive;

    // === Standard constructor (used elsewhere in the app) ===
    public Sensor(int id, String name, String type, float currentValue, boolean isActive) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.type = type;
        this.currentValue = currentValue;
        this.isActive = isActive;
    }

    // === Parcelable constructor (used by CREATOR) ===
    protected Sensor(Parcel in) {
        this.id           = in.readInt();
        this.name         = in.readString();
        this.type         = in.readString();
        this.currentValue = in.readFloat();
        this.isActive     = in.readByte() != 0; // boolean stored as byte
    }

    // === Getters ===
    public int getId() { return id; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public String getType() { return type; }
    public float getCurrentValue() { return currentValue; }
    public boolean isActive() { return isActive; }

    // === writeToParcel: serializes this object ===
    @Override
    public void writeToParcel(@NonNull Parcel dest, int flags) {
        dest.writeInt(id);
        dest.writeString(name);
        dest.writeString(type);
        dest.writeFloat(currentValue);
        dest.writeByte((byte) (isActive ? 1 : 0));
    }

    // === describeContents: usually 0 unless special objects in the parcel ===
    @Override
    public int describeContents() {
        return 0;
    }

    // === CREATOR: required static field; Android calls it to reconstruct objects ===
    public static final Creator<Sensor> CREATOR = new Creator<Sensor>() {
        @Override
        public Sensor createFromParcel(Parcel in) {
            return new Sensor(in);
        }

        @Override
        public Sensor[] newArray(int size) {
            return new Sensor[size];
        }
    };
}
```

