### ⭐ Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice [KTU University Exam - Model Paper 2024]

> **(a) With relevant code snippets, explain the modern approach to returning a result from a child activity to a parent activity in Android. Compare it with the deprecated `startActivityForResult` API. (7 marks) — [BT Level: Apply/Analyze]**

**Model Answer:**

**(i) The Deprecated API (2 marks):**

The legacy pattern (deprecated in AndroidX Activity 1.2.0) used three components:

```java
// Sender — OLD
Intent intent = new Intent(this, ChildActivity.class);
startActivityForResult(intent, 100);

// Receiver — OLD
Intent data = new Intent();
data.putExtra("RESULT_KEY", "RESULT_VALUE");
setResult(RESULT_OK, data);
finish();

// Sender callback — OLD
@Override
protected void onActivityResult(int requestCode, int resultCode, Intent data) {
    super.onActivityResult(requestCode, resultCode, data);
    if (requestCode == 100 && resultCode == RESULT_OK) {
        String result = data.getStringExtra("RESULT_KEY");
    }
}
```

**Problems:**
- `onActivityResult()` is called *before* the activity is fully resumed in some cases, causing UI inconsistencies.
- The request code is a magic int (collision-prone).
- Loses the result on configuration change unless manually persisted.

**(ii) The Modern API — `ActivityResultLauncher` (3 marks):**

```java
// 1. Declare the launcher as a class field
private final ActivityResultLauncher<Intent> childLauncher =
    registerForActivityResult(
        new ActivityResultContracts.StartActivityForResult(),
        result -> {
            if (result.getResultCode() == RESULT_OK && result.getData() != null) {
                String returned = result.getData().getStringExtra("RESULT_KEY");
                Log.d("Parent", "Got result: " + returned);
            }
        }
    );

// 2. Launch from a click
private void openChild() {
    Intent intent = new Intent(this, ChildActivity.class);
    childLauncher.launch(intent);
}

// 3. Child still uses setResult() (unchanged)
private void sendBack() {
    Intent data = new Intent();
    data.putExtra("RESULT_KEY", "RESULT_VALUE");
    setResult(RESULT_OK, data);
    finish();
}
```

**Advantages of the modern API:**
- Lifecycle-safe: result is delivered *only after* the activity is `STARTED`.
- Type-safe contracts via `ActivityResultContracts`.
- No magic request-code integers.
- Survives configuration changes automatically.
- Supports multiple launchers in the same activity without code duplication.

**(iii) Comparison Table (2 marks):**

| Aspect | Deprecated | Modern (2024) |
|---|---|---|
| Method | `startActivityForResult` | `registerForActivityResult` |
| Callback | `onActivityResult` | Lambda in `ActivityResultLauncher` |
| Lifecycle safety | No | Yes |
| Type safety | Weak (raw Intent) | Strong (Contract classes) |
| Code locality | Scattered (launch + callback in 2 methods) | Co-located in the launcher definition |

