> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls on "Passing Data to Intents" Questions**
> 
> **1. The "Parenthesis" Trap:**
> Many students write `getStringExtra("key")` but forget the **default value** parameter in `getIntExtra("key")`. Method signatures differ:
> - `getStringExtra(name)` — returns `null` if missing (no default)
> - `getIntExtra(name, defaultValue)` — **requires** a default
> - `getBooleanExtra(name, defaultValue)` — **requires** a default
> 
> Forgetting the default causes a **compilation error** and 0 marks for that code segment.
> 
> **2. The "Parcelable Order" Mistake:**
> Writing `dest.writeInt(id); dest.writeString(name);` in `writeToParcel()` but reading in a different order in the constructor causes **silent data corruption at runtime** — a 2-mark deduction.
> 
> **3. Confusing `getExtras()` vs `getIntent().getExtras()`:**
> `Activity.getIntent().getExtras()` returns the `Bundle`. Forgetting `getIntent()` first → `NullPointerException`. Lose 1 mark.
> 
> **4. Using `Serializable` Without Justification:**
> If a question says "production-quality IoT app", using `Serializable` for custom objects loses 1 mark for not preferring `Parcelable`.
> 
> **5. Missing `hasExtra()` Check:**
> Directly calling `getStringExtra()` without null-check loses 0.5–1 mark for lack of defensive programming.
> 
> **6. Parcel Size Limit Ignorance:**
> If asked about "passing large sensor logs", students who don't mention the **1 MB Binder limit** and propose Intent-based passing lose 2 marks for not recognizing the constraint.

