# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition

A **Broadcast Receiver** is one of the four fundamental Android application components (alongside Activity, Service, and Content Provider) that enables an application to **listen for and respond to system-wide or app-specific broadcast messages** sent via `Intents`. It acts as a dormant messaging gateway that gets activated by the Android system whenever a matching event of interest occurs, even if the parent application is not currently running in the foreground.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** Broadcast Receivers form the **event-driven backbone** of an IoT mobile application. They allow the app to react to external triggers such as incoming data from a remote sensor, Bluetooth device pairing events, network state changes, low-battery warnings, or custom-defined IoT command messages without requiring a continuously running polling service.

A broadcast is essentially a message wrapped in an `Intent` object that is sent via one of the system methods:
- `Context.sendBroadcast()` — Asynchronous, all receivers get it.
- `Context.sendOrderedBroadcast()` — Sequential, can be aborted by receivers.
- `Context.sendStickyBroadcast()` *(Deprecated since API 21)*.

## 1.2 Intuitive Real-World Analogy

Think of a **Broadcast Receiver like a postal mail notification system** registered at your home address:

| Real-World Concept | Android Equivalent |
|---|---|
| Your home address | The **Intent Filter** declared in the manifest |
| The post office | The **Android Framework** |
| A letter (event) | The **Intent object** |
| The mail slot/letterbox | The **BroadcastReceiver.onReceive()** callback |
| A signed registered letter | A **Permission-protected broadcast** |

Just as you might only open envelopes marked "Electricity Bill" or "Courier Delivery" and ignore junk mail, your Broadcast Receiver only triggers when an incoming Intent matches its declared filter criteria. The post office (Android system) doesn't care whether you are awake, asleep, or even at home — when a matching letter arrives, the system wakes up your mail slot, processes the letter, and notifies you.

In an **IoT scenario**, imagine a smart home app:
- A motion sensor detects movement → sends a broadcast.
- A "Motion Alert Receiver" registered in the app catches it → displays a notification, even if the app is closed.

This is the **publish-subscribe pattern** applied at the OS level.

## 1.3 Classification of Broadcasts

Broadcasts in Android are classified into two major families:

1. **System Broadcasts** — Issued by the Android OS itself.
   - Examples: `BOOT_COMPLETED`, `BATTERY_LOW`, `CONNECTIVITY_CHANGE`, `AIRPLANE_MODE`, `SMS_RECEIVED`.
2. **Custom (User-Defined) Broadcasts** — Issued by your own app or by a companion IoT device SDK.
   - Examples: `com.example.iot.SENSOR_DATA_READY`, `com.example.iot.DEVICE_DISCONNECTED`.

> [!NOTE]
> **Implicit vs Explicit Broadcasts:** An *implicit* broadcast targets any app whose filter matches (e.g., `ACTION_POWER_CONNECTED`). An *explicit* broadcast targets a specific application by ComponentName. Since **Android 8.0 (API 26)**, manifest-declared receivers for most implicit broadcasts are **no longer deliverable** to enforce resource efficiency. They must be registered dynamically at runtime.

---

**Constants and Standard Metrics:**

- **Default `onReceive()` execution time limit:** **10 seconds** (after which the OS may kill the process via ANR — Application Not Responding).
- **Recommendation:** Heavy work must be delegated to a `JobIntentService`, `WorkManager`, or `goAsync()` pattern.
- **Manifest receiver tag:** `<receiver>`.
- **Permission attribute:** `android:permission` (e.g., `android.permission.RECEIVE_SMS`).
