# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 The BroadcastReceiver Lifecycle — The "Why" and "How"

The lifecycle of a BroadcastReceiver is fundamentally different from an Activity. A receiver does **not** have a user interface, does not persist between invocations, and is created/destroyed on every broadcast event.

### Step-by-Step Operational Logic:

1. **Declaration Phase** — The developer declares a receiver either:
   - **Statically** in `AndroidManifest.xml` using the `<receiver>` tag, OR
   - **Dynamically** at runtime via `Context.registerReceiver()`.
2. **Registration Phase** — The OS indexes the receiver's `IntentFilter` rules. The system matches every broadcast Intent against all registered filters.
3. **Trigger Phase** — When a matching Intent is broadcast, the Android framework instantiates the receiver class (if not already alive) and invokes its `onReceive(Context, Intent)` method.
4. **Execution Phase** — The receiver processes the Intent extras. It has a strict **~10 second window** to complete work.
5. **Termination Phase** — The receiver instance is marked eligible for garbage collection. If the process has no other active components, Android may kill the process.

> [!TIP]
> **Why the 10-second limit?** Android treats receivers as lightweight glue code. Long operations can starve the main thread, causing UI freezes or ANRs. For IoT data processing, use `goAsync()` to extend the window up to ~10 seconds with a `PendingResult` object.

## 2.2 Registration Methods — Statically vs Dynamically

### A. Static (Manifest) Registration
Suitable for **always-on** event triggers that should wake the app even after reboot.

```xml
<receiver
    android:name=".MotionAlertReceiver"
    android:exported="true">
    <intent-filter>
        <action android:name="com.example.iot.MOTION_DETECTED" />
    </intent-filter>
</receiver>
```

### B. Dynamic (Runtime) Registration
Suitable for **lifecycle-bound** event listening (e.g., only when an Activity is visible).

```java
IntentFilter filter = new IntentFilter("com.example.iot.MOTION_DETECTED");
MotionAlertReceiver receiver = new MotionAlertReceiver();
registerReceiver(receiver, filter);
```

**Unregistration is mandatory:**
```java
@Override
protected void onPause() {
    super.onPause();
    unregisterReceiver(receiver);
}
```

> [!WARNING]
> Forgetting to unregister a dynamically registered receiver causes a **memory leak** and crashes the app with `IllegalArgumentException: Receiver not registered`.

## 2.3 Security Model & Android Version Constraints

| Android Version | Key Restriction |
|---|---|
| API 25 (7.1) and below | Manifest registration works for all implicit broadcasts. |
| API 26 (8.0 Oreo) | Most implicit broadcasts **cannot** be received via manifest. Must use dynamic registration or `JobScheduler`. |
| API 33 (13 Tiramisu) | New flags `RECEIVER_EXPORTED` / `RECEIVER_NOT_EXPORTED` are **mandatory** for runtime registration. |
| API 34 (14 Upside Down Cake) | Stricter enforcement of receiver export flags; explicit `RECEIVER_EXPORTED` required for cross-app broadcasts. |

## 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

Since this is a programmatic concept, the "formula" sheet covers the essential API and contract parameters.

| **Parameter / Method** | **Type** | **Purpose / Unit** |
|---|---|---|
| `BroadcastReceiver` | Abstract Class | Base class to extend. |
| `onReceive(Context, Intent)` | Callback Method | Entry point; **max ~10 sec** execution. |
| `IntentFilter` | Class | Declares matching `Action`, `Category`, `Data` URI. |
| `Context.sendBroadcast(Intent)` | Method | Fire-and-forget async broadcast. |
| `sendOrderedBroadcast(Intent, String)` | Method | Sequential delivery; passes result to next receiver. |
| `registerReceiver(BroadcastReceiver, IntentFilter)` | Method | Runtime registration. |
| `unregisterReceiver(BroadcastReceiver)` | Method | Mandatory cleanup. |
| `goAsync()` | Method | Returns `PendingResult`; extends work window. |
| `RECEIVER_EXPORTED` | Constant (int = 2) | Required flag for cross-app broadcasts (API 33+). |
| `RECEIVER_NOT_EXPORTED` | Constant (int = 4) | Receiver limited to same UID (API 33+). |
| `<receiver>` | Manifest Tag | Static declaration. |
| `android:permission` | Manifest Attribute | Receiver execution requires this permission. |
| `android:exported` | Manifest Attribute | Whether receiver is callable by other apps. |
| `PendingResult` | Inner Class | Handle for async work after `onReceive()`. |

## 2.5 Real-World IoT Utility

In IoT systems, Broadcast Receivers serve as the **local edge-event dispatcher**:

- **BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy):** Receivers handle `BluetoothDevice.ACTION_FOUND` and `ACTION_GATT_CONNECTED`.
- **Wi-Fi provisioning:** Catch `WifiManager.NETWORK_STATE_CHANGED_ACTION` to react to network drops.
- **MQTT integration:** A custom broadcast from a background MQTT service (`MqttMessageArrived`) is dispatched to UI fragments via a local broadcast.
- **Geofencing:** `LocationManager` triggers `com.google.android.gms.location.Geofence` transitions via broadcasts.
- **Custom IoT protocols:** Proprietary device-to-cloud SDKs use broadcasts to notify the UI layer of telemetry updates without tight coupling.
