# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**

**Q1. Define a Broadcast Receiver in Android. Mention any two system broadcasts used in IoT applications.**

**Model Answer:**
A Broadcast Receiver is an Android component that listens for and responds to system-wide or app-specific broadcast messages (Intents). It is one of the four main Android components alongside Activity, Service, and Content Provider. It is declared by extending the `android.content.BroadcastReceiver` class and overriding the `onReceive()` method.

Two system broadcasts commonly used in IoT:
1. `android.net.conn.CONNECTIVITY_CHANGE` — Triggered when the device's network connectivity changes (e.g., Wi-Fi ↔ Mobile data handover).
2. `android.bluetooth.device.action.ACL_CONNECTED` — Triggered when a Bluetooth device (such as a BLE sensor) establishes a connection.

---

> **[KTU University Exam – June 2024]**

**Q2. Differentiate between static and dynamic broadcast receiver registration. State one limitation of each.**

**Model Answer:**

| Aspect | Static (Manifest) | Dynamic (Runtime) |
|---|---|---|
| Declaration | `<receiver>` tag in `AndroidManifest.xml` | `registerReceiver()` call in code |
| Lifetime | App install → uninstall | Activity `onCreate` → `onDestroy` |
| Receives when app is killed? | Yes | No |

**Limitation of Static Registration:** Most implicit system broadcasts are restricted on Android 8.0 (API 26) and above — manifest-registered receivers for these will not be invoked.
**Limitation of Dynamic Registration:** It does not survive process death; if the OS kills the app, the receiver is unregistered automatically and the event is lost.

---

## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Internal Choice)

> **[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 — Module 3, Q11]**

### **Question A (14 Marks)**

**(a)** Explain the lifecycle of an Android Broadcast Receiver with a neat diagram. Mention the role of the `onReceive()` method. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete Android program (manifest entry + Java class) to create a custom Broadcast Receiver named `MotionAlertReceiver` that listens for the action `com.example.iot.MOTION_DETECTED` and displays a Toast with the location ID passed as an extra. **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution

**(a) Lifecycle of a Broadcast Receiver:**

The lifecycle of a Broadcast Receiver consists of three main phases:

1. **Registration Phase:** The receiver is registered either statically (in `AndroidManifest.xml` via the `<receiver>` element) or dynamically (in code via `Context.registerReceiver()`).
2. **Reception & onReceive() Phase:** When a matching broadcast Intent is dispatched, the Android framework instantiates the receiver (if needed) and invokes the `onReceive(Context context, Intent intent)` callback. This method runs on the **main thread** of the application process and has a **maximum execution window of approximately 10 seconds**.
3. **Termination Phase:** After `onReceive()` returns, the receiver instance is eligible for garbage collection. If the application process has no other active components, Android may kill it to reclaim memory.

**Role of `onReceive()`:** It is the **sole entry point** of the receiver. It receives the broadcast `Intent` and any associated extras. All initial processing of the broadcast event must occur here, or be delegated via `goAsync()` to a background thread.

```
Registration ──► Matching Intent ──► onReceive() ──► GC / Process Killed
```

**(b) Program Code:**

**`AndroidManifest.xml` (relevant excerpt):**
```xml
<receiver
    android:name=".MotionAlertReceiver"
    android:exported="false">
    <intent-filter>
        <action android:name="com.example.iot.MOTION_DETECTED" />
    </intent-filter>
</receiver>
```

**`MotionAlertReceiver.java`:**
```java
package com.example.iotapp;

import android.content.BroadcastReceiver;
import android.content.Context;
import android.content.Intent;
import android.widget.Toast;

public class MotionAlertReceiver extends BroadcastReceiver {
    @Override
    public void onReceive(Context context, Intent intent) {
        String action = intent.getAction();
        if ("com.example.iot.MOTION_DETECTED".equals(action)) {
            String locationId = intent.getStringExtra("location_id");
            if (locationId == null) locationId = "Unknown";
            Toast.makeText(context,
                "Motion detected at: " + locationId,
                Toast.LENGTH_LONG).show();
        }
    }
}
```

**Optional sending code (for testing):**
```java
Intent i = new Intent("com.example.iot.MOTION_DETECTED");
i.putExtra("location_id", "Lobby_01");
sendBroadcast(i);
```

---

### **Question B (14 Marks)** — *Alternative Choice*

**(a)** With a neat diagram, explain the different methods of registering a Broadcast Receiver in Android. Compare their use cases in an IoT application. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Discuss the security model of Broadcast Receivers in Android, including the impact of Android 8.0 (API 26) and Android 13 (API 33) restrictions. How would you secure a custom IoT broadcast? **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution

**(a) Methods of Registration — Diagram + Comparison:**

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Receiver Registration] --> B[Static - Manifest]
    A --> C[Dynamic - Runtime]
    B --> B1[Declared via receiver tag]
    B --> B2[Persists across app restarts]
    B --> B3[Receives even if app is killed]
    C --> C1[Declared via registerReceiver]
    C --> C2[Tied to Activity lifecycle]
    C --> C3[Must unregister in onPause]
```

**Static (Manifest) Registration:**
The receiver is declared in `AndroidManifest.xml` using the `<receiver>` tag. It is parsed at install time. It can receive broadcasts even when the application is not running. Example use case in IoT: A `BootCompletedReceiver` that initializes MQTT client connection after the device reboots.

**Dynamic (Runtime) Registration:**
The receiver is registered programmatically in Java/Kotlin using `context.registerReceiver()`. It is tied to the lifecycle of a `Context` (typically an Activity). It must be unregistered to avoid memory leaks. Example use case in IoT: A `SensorDataReceiver` listening for telemetry updates only while the dashboard Activity is in the foreground.

**Comparison Table:**

| Feature | Static | Dynamic |
|---|---|---|
| Triggers when app is killed? | Yes | No |
| Lifecycle management | Automatic | Manual |
| Use case in IoT | Boot-time, alarm-based events | UI-bound live data updates |

**(b) Security Model and Version-Specific Restrictions:**

**Android 8.0 (API 26) Impact:**
- Most implicit system broadcasts (e.g., `CONNECTIVITY_CHANGE`, `NEW_PICTURE`) can no longer be registered in the manifest.
- This was introduced to prevent background apps from being woken up by frequent system events, conserving battery and memory.
- Solution: Use **dynamic registration** in an Activity/Service, or schedule work via `JobScheduler` / `WorkManager`.

**Android 13 (API 33) Impact:**
- When using `registerReceiver()` at runtime, the developer **must** explicitly specify the receiver's exported state using one of:
  - `Context.RECEIVER_EXPORTED` (int = 2) — Receiver can receive broadcasts from other apps.
  - `Context.RECEIVER_NOT_EXPORTED` (int = 4) — Receiver only receives broadcasts from the same UID.
- Failing to specify these flags results in a `SecurityException` at runtime.

**Securing a Custom IoT Broadcast:**

1. **Define a custom permission** in the manifest:
   ```xml
   <permission
       android:name="com.example.iot.permission.SENSOR_DATA"
       android:protectionLevel="signature" />
   ```
2. **Enforce it when sending:**
   ```java
   sendBroadcast(intent, "com.example.iot.permission.SENSOR_DATA");
   ```
3. **Require it on the receiver side:**
   ```xml
   <uses-permission android:name="com.example.iot.permission.SENSOR_DATA" />
   ```
4. **Set `android:exported="false"`** if the receiver is only meant for internal use.
5. **Validate the action and extras** in `onReceive()` to defend against spoofed Intents.

Using `signature`-level protection ensures only apps signed with the **same certificate** can send or receive the broadcast — a robust security boundary in a multi-app IoT ecosystem.

---

## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mark-Deduction Traps in Broadcast Receiver Questions:**
> 1. **Forgetting `unregisterReceiver()`** → Memory leak / crash on second registration. (–1 to –2 marks)
> 2. **Missing the Android 13 `RECEIVER_EXPORTED` flag** in code snippets. (–2 marks — increasingly tested from 2024 onwards)
> 3. **Using `setComponent()` for custom broadcasts** — this makes the broadcast *explicit*; the question usually expects *implicit* (action-based) filter matching. (–1 mark)
> 4. **Not distinguishing manifest vs dynamic registration** in theory answers — examiners award marks for *explicit comparison*. (–1 to –3 marks)
> 5. **Performing network calls directly inside `onReceive()` without `goAsync()`** — flagged as an anti-pattern. (–1 mark)
> 6. **Omitting the `intent-filter` for static receivers** — receiver is never triggered. (–2 marks)

---

## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- A **Broadcast Receiver** is a passive component that responds to broadcast Intents; it has no UI.
- The **only mandatory callback** is `onReceive(Context, Intent)`, which runs on the **main thread** with a **~10-second execution budget**.
- **Two registration methods** exist: **static (manifest)** for app-wide persistent listening, and **dynamic (runtime)** for lifecycle-bound listening.
- **Android 8.0+ restricts implicit manifest broadcasts**; use dynamic registration or `JobScheduler`/`WorkManager`.
- **Android 13+ requires `RECEIVER_EXPORTED` / `RECEIVER_NOT_EXPORTED` flags** for runtime registration.
- **Always unregister** dynamically registered receivers (typically in `onPause()`) to prevent memory leaks.
- For long-running work, use **`goAsync()` + `pendingResult.finish()`** to extend the execution window safely.
- Secure custom broadcasts with **custom signature-level permissions** and **`android:exported="false"`** by default.
- Broadcast types: `sendBroadcast()` (async, all), `sendOrderedBroadcast()` (sequential, prioritizable, abortable).
- For IoT apps, receivers are the **primary glue** between sensors/devices and the UI layer — they enable event-driven, low-power architectures.
- KTU 2024 pattern: expect a **definition + lifecycle question (3 marks)** and an **implementation + comparison question (14 marks)** with internal choice.
