# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Building a Custom Content Provider — Full Derivation

The following derivation walks through the **complete construction** of a Content Provider for an IoT sensor-logging application. Every step is explicit — no shortcuts.

### Step 1: Define the Contract Class

A *Contract* class is a public, static container of constants that both the provider and its clients share. This avoids "magic strings" scattered throughout the codebase.

```java
public final class SensorLogContract {

    private SensorLogContract() {}  // Prevent instantiation

    public static final String AUTHORITY = "com.ktu.iot.sensorlog";
    public static final Uri BASE_CONTENT_URI =
            Uri.parse("content://" + AUTHORITY);

    public static final String PATH_READINGS = "readings";

    public static final class ReadingsEntry implements BaseColumns {
        public static final Uri CONTENT_URI =
                BASE_CONTENT_URI.buildUpon().appendPath(PATH_READINGS).build();

        public static final String TABLE_NAME = "readings";
        public static final String COLUMN_DEVICE_ID  = "device_id";
        public static final String COLUMN_SENSOR_TYPE = "sensor_type";
        public static final String COLUMN_VALUE      = "value";
        public static final String COLUMN_TIMESTAMP  = "timestamp";
    }
}
```

> **Logic note:** `BaseColumns` is a marker interface that auto-supplies the conventional `_ID` and `_COUNT` columns, which Android adapters such as `CursorAdapter` expect.

### Step 2: Implement the SQLite Helper

The provider needs a backing store. Here, a `SQLiteOpenHelper` is used.

```java
public class SensorLogDbHelper extends SQLiteOpenHelper {
    public static final String DATABASE_NAME = "sensorlog.db";
    public static final int DATABASE_VERSION = 1;

    private static final String SQL_CREATE_TABLE =
        "CREATE TABLE " + SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME + " (" +
        SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry._ID + " INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT, " +
        SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_DEVICE_ID  + " TEXT NOT NULL, " +
        SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_SENSOR_TYPE + " TEXT NOT NULL, " +
        SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_VALUE      + " REAL NOT NULL, " +
        SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP  + " INTEGER NOT NULL" +
        ");";

    public SensorLogDbHelper(Context context) {
        super(context, DATABASE_NAME, null, DATABASE_VERSION);
    }

    @Override public void onCreate(SQLiteDatabase db) { db.execSQL(SQL_CREATE_TABLE); }

    @Override public void onUpgrade(SQLiteDatabase db, int oldV, int newV) {
        db.execSQL("DROP TABLE IF EXISTS " + SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME);
        onCreate(db);
    }
}
```

> **Logic note:** `INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT` is the canonical way to get an auto-incrementing row ID in SQLite, which Android uses as the row identifier in the URI.

### Step 3: Build the `UriMatcher`

The `UriMatcher` is the routing table of the provider. It translates incoming URIs into integer codes used in a `switch` statement.

```java
private static final int CODE_READINGS      = 100;   // content://.../readings
private static final int CODE_READING_BY_ID = 101;   // content://.../readings/42

private static final UriMatcher URI_MATCHER = new UriMatcher(UriMatcher.NO_MATCH);

static {
    URI_MATCHER.addURI(SensorLogContract.AUTHORITY,
                       SensorLogContract.PATH_READINGS, CODE_READINGS);
    URI_MATCHER.addURI(SensorLogContract.AUTHORITY,
                       SensorLogContract.PATH_READINGS + "/#", CODE_READING_BY_ID);
}
```

> **Logic note:** The `#` wildcard matches any numeric path segment. For string IDs, you would use `*` instead. `NO_MATCH = -1` is the safe default returned when no rule applies.

### Step 4: Implement the Four CRUD Methods Explicitly

#### 3.1.1 Insert — Derivation

The client supplies a `ContentValues` map. The provider must:

1. **Validate** the URI matches the collection URI (`CODE_READINGS`).
2. **Open** a writable database.
3. **Insert** the row; the database returns the new primary-key value `id`.
4. **Construct** the new row URI: `CONTENT_URI.buildUpon().appendPath(String.valueOf(id)).build()`.
5. **Notify** any observers that the table changed.

```java
@Override
public Uri insert(Uri uri, ContentValues values) {
    final int match = URI_MATCHER.match(uri);
    Uri returnUri;

    if (match != CODE_READINGS) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid URI for insert: " + uri);
    }

    SQLiteDatabase db = mDbHelper.getWritableDatabase();
    long id = db.insert(SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME, null, values);

    if (id <= 0) {
        throw new android.database.SQLException("Insert failed for URI: " + uri);
    }

    returnUri = ContentUris.withAppendedId(
                   SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.CONTENT_URI, id);

    getContext().getContentResolver().notifyChange(uri, null);
    return returnUri;
}
```

**Textual logic for each line:**

| Line | Reasoning |
|---|---|
| `URI_MATCHER.match(uri)` | Convert the URI string to a routable integer. |
| `if (match != CODE_READINGS)` | Reject any URI that doesn't target the full table. |
| `getWritableDatabase()` | Acquire an exclusive write handle; lazily creates the DB if absent. |
| `db.insert(...)` | Returns the new row's `_ID`, or `-1` on failure. |
| `ContentUris.withAppendedId(...)` | Standard Android helper to glue the new ID onto the base URI. |
| `notifyChange(uri, null)` | Tells the system to refresh any active `CursorLoader`s. |

#### 3.1.2 Retrieve (Query) — Derivation

```java
@Override
public Cursor query(Uri uri, String[] projection, String selection,
                    String[] selectionArgs, String sortOrder) {

    SQLiteDatabase db = mDbHelper.getReadableDatabase();
    Cursor retCursor;
    int match = URI_MATCHER.match(uri);

    switch (match) {
        case CODE_READINGS:
            retCursor = db.query(
                SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME,
                projection, selection, selectionArgs,
                null, null, sortOrder);
            break;

        case CODE_READING_BY_ID:
            long id = ContentUris.parseId(uri);   // Extracts "42" from .../readings/42
            String idSelection = SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry._ID + "=?";
            String[] idArgs = new String[]{ String.valueOf(id) };
            retCursor = db.query(
                SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME,
                projection, idSelection, idArgs,
                null, null, sortOrder);
            break;

        default:
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Cannot query unknown URI: " + uri);
    }

    retCursor.setNotificationUri(getContext().getContentResolver(), uri);
    return retCursor;
}
```

> **Logic note:** `setNotificationUri(...)` binds the cursor to the URI so that a subsequent `notifyChange()` triggers an automatic re-query in any active `CursorLoader` consumer.

#### 3.1.3 Update — Derivation

```java
@Override
public int update(Uri uri, ContentValues values, String selection,
                  String[] selectionArgs) {
    int match = URI_MATCHER.match(uri);
    int rowsUpdated;
    SQLiteDatabase db = mDbHelper.getWritableDatabase();

    switch (match) {
        case CODE_READINGS:
            rowsUpdated = db.update(
                SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME,
                values, selection, selectionArgs);
            break;

        case CODE_READING_BY_ID:
            long id = ContentUris.parseId(uri);
            String idSelection = SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry._ID + "=?";
            String[] idArgs = new String[]{ String.valueOf(id) };
            rowsUpdated = db.update(
                SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME,
                values, idSelection, idArgs);
            break;

        default:
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Cannot update unknown URI: " + uri);
    }

    if (rowsUpdated > 0) {
        getContext().getContentResolver().notifyChange(uri, null);
    }
    return rowsUpdated;
}
```

> **Logic note:** The **return value is the count of rows actually modified** — not the count of rows that matched the WHERE clause. If a `ContentValues` is identical to existing data, the count may be `0` even when rows matched.

#### 3.1.4 Delete — Derivation

```java
@Override
public int delete(Uri uri, String selection, String[] selectionArgs) {
    int match = URI_MATCHER.match(uri);
    int rowsDeleted;
    SQLiteDatabase db = mDbHelper.getWritableDatabase();

    switch (match) {
        case CODE_READINGS:
            rowsDeleted = db.delete(
                SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME,
                selection, selectionArgs);
            break;

        case CODE_READING_BY_ID:
            long id = ContentUris.parseId(uri);
            String idSelection = SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry._ID + "=?";
            String[] idArgs = new String[]{ String.valueOf(id) };
            rowsDeleted = db.delete(
                SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.TABLE_NAME,
                idSelection, idArgs);
            break;

        default:
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Cannot delete unknown URI: " + uri);
    }

    if (rowsDeleted > 0) {
        getContext().getContentResolver().notifyChange(uri, null);
    }
    return rowsDeleted;
}
```

### Step 5: Client-Side Usage Patterns

The **client** of this provider only ever sees the `ContentResolver`:

```java
ContentResolver resolver = getContentResolver();

// INSERT
ContentValues cv = new ContentValues();
cv.put(SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_DEVICE_ID,  "ESP32-A4");
cv.put(SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_SENSOR_TYPE,"temperature");
cv.put(SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_VALUE,       27.4);
cv.put(SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP,  System.currentTimeMillis());
Uri newUri = resolver.insert(SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.CONTENT_URI, cv);

// RETRIEVE
Cursor c = resolver.query(
    SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.CONTENT_URI,
    null,                              // projection = all columns
    SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_SENSOR_TYPE + " = ?",
    new String[]{ "temperature" },
    SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP + " DESC"
);
while (c.moveToNext()) {
    String dev  = c.getString(c.getColumnIndexOrThrow(
        SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_DEVICE_ID));
    double val  = c.getDouble(c.getColumnIndexOrThrow(
        SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_VALUE));
    Log.d("IOT", dev + " reported " + val);
}
c.close();

// UPDATE
ContentValues upd = new ContentValues();
upd.put(SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_VALUE, 28.1);
int n = resolver.update(
    SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.CONTENT_URI,
    upd,
    SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_DEVICE_ID + " = ?",
    new String[]{ "ESP32-A4" }
);

// DELETE
int d = resolver.delete(
    SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.CONTENT_URI,
    SensorLogContract.ReadingsEntry.COLUMN_TIMESTAMP + " < ?",
    new String[]{ String.valueOf(System.currentTimeMillis() - 86_400_000L) }
);
```
