## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition**
> An **IoT Mobile Application** is a software program designed to run on a mobile operating system (Android/iOS) that establishes a network-mediated communication channel with resource-constrained IoT endpoints (sensors, actuators, micro-controllers) to perform telemetry acquisition, remote actuation, data visualization, and real-time device orchestration. In the context of the KTU PECGT415 practical lab, a "Simple IoT Mobile App" is defined as a minimal Android-based client that uses the **MQTT (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport)** publish/subscribe protocol over TCP/IP to exchange JSON-formatted telemetry and command payloads with an MQTT broker, which in turn relays messages to an IoT device (typically an ESP8266/ESP32 node running a PubSubClient sketch).

In strict KTU 2024 Scheme terminology, the practical lab assessment evaluates the learner's ability to:
1. Configure the **Android Studio IDE** with the necessary SDKs (minSdkVersion 24, targetSdkVersion 34).
2. Integrate a third-party MQTT client library such as **Eclipse Paho Android Service** (`org.eclipse.paho:org.eclipse.paho.android.service:1.1.1`).
3. Implement **asynchronous network I/O** on the Android main thread without violating `StrictMode` policies.
4. Parse **JSON telemetry** using `org.json.JSONObject`.
5. Update the **UI thread** safely using `Handler.post()` or `LiveData` from Android Architecture Components.

---

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The "Smart Postman" Mental Model

> [!NOTE]
> **Plain-English Analogy**
> Imagine a smart post office in the middle of a city. The **post office** is the **MQTT broker** (e.g., Mosquitto, HiveMQ Cloud). **Citizens** are the **IoT devices** (sensors, ESP32 boards). Each citizen has a unique **P.O. Box number** — this is the **MQTT Topic** (e.g., `home/livingroom/temperature`). The **mobile app** is a citizen who can drop letters into any P.O. Box (`PUBLISH`) or ask the postmaster to forward any letter arriving in a particular box to them (`SUBSCRIBE`).
>
> - **Sensor → Broker**: "Hey postmaster, my temperature reading is 28.5 °C. Put this letter in box `sensor/temp`."
> - **Mobile App → Broker**: "Postmaster, please forward every letter that arrives in `sensor/temp` to me."
> - **Mobile App → Actuator**: "Postmaster, deliver this letter ('turn ON the fan') to box `actuator/fan/cmd`."
>
> This **decoupled architecture** is what makes MQTT ideal for IoT — the mobile app never talks to the device directly. The broker handles the routing. This is fundamentally different from the old HTTP request-response model where you'd have to "knock on the door" of every device.

---

### 1.3 Key Physical / Network Parameters

The following **mandatory parameters** must be committed to memory for the KTU lab viva and ESE:

| Parameter | Typical Value | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| **Default MQTT Port (Plaintext)** | **1883** | Unencrypted TCP communication |
| **Default MQTT Port (TLS)** | **8883** | Encrypted communication using SSL/TLS |
| **MQTT QoS Level 0** | At most once | Fire-and-forget, no ACK |
| **MQTT QoS Level 1** | At least once | PUBACK handshake, possible duplicates |
| **MQTT QoS Level 2** | Exactly once | Four-step handshake, no duplicates |
| **Keep-Alive Interval** | **60 seconds** | PINGREQ packet sent by client to broker |
| **Last Will and Testament (LWT)** | Custom payload | Broker publishes this on unexpected client disconnect |
| **Clean Session Flag** | `true` / `false` | Whether broker persists subscriptions for the client |
| **Android `minSdkVersion`** | **24 (Android 7.0)** | KTU lab minimum baseline |
| **JSON Payload Size** | < 1 KB typical | Keep telemetry small to conserve battery |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Syllabus Highlight — The "Big 3" Components of the Lab**
