## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Three-Layer Reference Architecture

The lab exercise is built on a **decoupled three-tier architecture**. Understanding this is the single most important conceptual requirement for scoring the 14-mark ESE question on this topic.

> [!NOTE]
> **Layer 1 — Perception Layer (Hardware End)**
> Comprises physical sensors (DHT11, LM35, PIR, LDR) and actuators (relay, LED, motor driver) interfaced to a micro-controller (ESP8266/ESP32/Arduino Uno + ESP-01 shield). The firmware uses a lightweight MQTT client (e.g., PubSubClient for Arduino) to connect to the broker over Wi-Fi.

> [!NOTE]
> **Layer 2 — Network Layer (Broker / Cloud)**
> The MQTT broker (Mosquitto, EMQX, HiveMQ, AWS IoT Core) acts as a message router. It accepts TCP connections on port 1883, manages client sessions, enforces ACLs, and forwards published messages to all subscribers of matching topics. The broker is **protocol-agnostic** to the application payload — it only inspects the topic string.

> [!NOTE]
> **Layer 3 — Application Layer (Mobile Client)**
> The Android app running the Eclipse Paho client library. It binds a `MqttAndroidClient` to a unique Client ID, subscribes to one or more topic filters, registers a callback to handle incoming messages, and updates the UI via `TextView`/`Chart` widgets.

---

### 2.2 Operational Workflow — The "Connect–Subscribe–Receive–Publish" Lifecycle

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why this sequence matters in the KTU exam:**
> The KTU board examiner will award marks ONLY if your answer mirrors this canonical lifecycle. Memorize the four verbs in order: **CSSR** — *Connect, Subscribe, Subscribe-callback, Receive, React, Publish*.

The full lifecycle executed by the Android client is:

1. **Connect**: The app calls `mqttClient.connect(options)`, passing an `MqttConnectOptions` object containing the broker URI, username/password (if any), clean session flag, and keep-alive interval. The Paho library performs an underlying `MQTT CONNECT` packet exchange.
2. **Subscribe**: On successful connection, the app calls `mqttClient.subscribe(topic, qos)` for each topic of interest (e.g., `"iot/sensor/temp"`, QoS 1). The broker responds with a `SUBACK` packet.
3. **Callback Registration**: The app registers an `MqttCallbackExtended` listener. The Paho library dispatches incoming `PUBLISH` packets to this listener on a background thread.
4. **Receive & Parse**: Inside `messageArrived()`, the app receives an `MqttMessage`, extracts the `byte[] payload`, converts to a UTF-8 string, parses it as a `JSONObject`, and extracts fields (e.g., `temperature`, `humidity`).
5. **UI Update**: The parsed value is forwarded to the main thread using `runOnUiThread()` or `Handler.post()` to update a `TextView`/`SeekBar`.
6. **Publish (Control)**: When the user taps a button (e.g., "Turn ON LED"), the app constructs an `MqttMessage` with a JSON payload like `{"command":"ON"}` and calls `mqttClient.publish("iot/actuator/led", message)`.

