### 3.5 Phase 5 — Companion ESP8266/ESP32 Arduino Sketch (For Context)

Although the KTU practical focuses on the **mobile client**, examiners often ask you to explain the device-side firmware. The minimal Arduino sketch is:

```cpp
#include <PubSubClient.h>
#include <ESP8266WiFi.h>

const char* ssid = "KTU_LAB_WIFI";
const char* pass = "labpassword";
const char* mqttServer = "test.mosquitto.org";

WiFiClient espClient;
PubSubClient client(espClient);

void callback(char* topic, byte* payload, unsigned int length) {
    // Parse {"command":"ON"} and toggle GPIO2 (on-board LED)
    String msg = "";
    for (int i = 0; i < length; i++) msg += (char)payload[i];
    if (msg == "{\"command\":\"ON\"}")  digitalWrite(2, LOW);
    if (msg == "{\"command\":\"OFF\"}") digitalWrite(2, HIGH);
}

void setup() {
    pinMode(2, OUTPUT);
    WiFi.begin(ssid, pass);
    while (WiFi.status() != WL_CONNECTED) delay(500);
    client.setServer(mqttServer, 1883);
    client.setCallback(callback);
    client.connect("ESP8266_KTU");
    client.subscribe("ktu/lab/actuator/led");
}

void loop() {
    client.loop();
    if (millis() % 10000 == 0) {  // publish every 10 s
        client.publish("ktu/lab/sensor/temp", 
            "{\"temperature\":28.5}");
    }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why the `client.loop()` call matters**:
> In the Paho embedded client, the main Arduino `loop()` must explicitly call `client.loop()` to process incoming MQTT packets. This is **NOT** required on Android because the Paho Android Service runs its own background thread. This asymmetry is a classic viva question.
