### 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (2 × 3 = 6 Marks)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam – May 2024 Model]**
*Define the term "MQTT Topic" with a suitable example used in your IoT mobile app lab. Also list the two wildcards supported by MQTT and explain the difference between them.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

> [!NOTE]
> An **MQTT topic** is a UTF-8 string used by the broker to filter messages for connected clients. Each topic consists of one or more topic levels separated by the forward slash `/`. Example used in lab: `ktu/lab/sensor/temp` — the publishing client (ESP8266) sends telemetry to this topic, and the Android app subscribes to the same string to receive the data.
>
> MQTT supports two wildcards:
> 1. **Single-level wildcard `+`**: Matches exactly one topic level. Example: subscribing to `ktu/+/temp` will match `ktu/lab/temp` and `ktu/home/temp` but NOT `ktu/lab/sensor/temp`.
> 2. **Multi-level wildcard `#`**: Matches one or more remaining topic levels. Example: subscribing to `ktu/#` matches every topic starting with `ktu/`. The `#` must always be the last character in the topic filter.

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 Model]**
*What is the role of the Eclipse Paho library in your lab implementation? Why can't you use raw Java `Socket` programming to talk to an MQTT broker directly?*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

> [!NOTE]
> The **Eclipse Paho Android Service** library (`org.eclipse.paho.android.service`) is a third-party MQTT client implementation that handles the entire MQTT 3.1.1 protocol stack — including `CONNECT/CONNACK` packet assembly, **Quality of Service (QoS)** handshake management, **keep-alive** ping scheduling, **Last Will and Testament (LWT)** configuration, and asynchronous message delivery via background threads.
>
> You cannot use raw `java.net.Socket` programming because MQTT has a **binary protocol** with fixed 2-byte headers, variable-length encoding, and strict state machine semantics. Implementing this from scratch would require manually packing bits, computing packet identifiers, and managing retransmission timers. Paho encapsulates this complexity behind a clean `MqttAndroidClient` API. Using raw sockets would also force the developer to perform network I/O on the main thread, triggering Android's `NetworkOnMainThreadException` and violating the platform's threading model.

