**Question A (14 Marks)**
*`[KTU University Exam – May 2024 Model]`*

**(a)** With a neat block diagram, explain the three-tier architecture of the IoT mobile app you developed in your lab. Label all communication protocols and port numbers used. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write the step-by-step procedure to develop the Android client, including the Gradle dependency, manifest permissions, and the `messageArrived()` callback implementation. Show how JSON parsing is performed. **(7 marks)**

**Model Answer:**

**(a) Three-Tier Architecture (7 marks):**

The IoT mobile app lab implements a **three-tier decoupled architecture**:

- **Tier 1 — Perception Layer**: An ESP8266/ESP32 micro-controller reads temperature data from a DHT11 sensor and receives control commands for an LED actuator connected to GPIO2. This layer interfaces directly with the physical world.
- **Tier 2 — Network Layer**: A public MQTT broker (`test.mosquitto.org`) listens on TCP port **1883**. The ESP8266 publishes telemetry to the topic `ktu/lab/sensor/temp` with QoS 1. The broker maintains a session table and forwards the message to all clients subscribed to matching topics.
- **Tier 3 — Application Layer**: An Android app (minSdkVersion 24) uses the Eclipse Paho client to connect to the broker using a unique Client ID. It subscribes to `ktu/lab/sensor/temp`, parses incoming JSON, and updates a `TextView` on the main thread. UI button taps publish control JSON to `ktu/lab/actuator/led`.

Communication protocol between Tier 1 and Tier 2 is **Wi-Fi (IEEE 802.11 b/g/n) carrying MQTT over TCP**. Between Tier 2 and Tier 3, the same MQTT-over-TCP is used. The **default plaintext MQTT port is 1883**; the encrypted TLS port is 8883 (not used in basic lab).

