**Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice**
*`[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 Model]`*

**(a)** Explain the MQTT protocol packet structure. Differentiate between QoS levels 0, 1, and 2 with respect to packet exchanges. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Design and explain the JSON payload schema for an IoT app that monitors three sensors (temperature, humidity, light) and controls two actuators (fan, bulb). Show the subscribe and publish topic hierarchy you would use. **(7 marks)**

**Model Answer:**

**(a) MQTT Packet Structure and QoS Levels (7 marks):**

Every MQTT control packet has a **Fixed Header** (minimum 2 bytes), an optional **Variable Header**, and a **Payload**. The fixed header contains a 1-byte control packet type (4 bits) + flags (4 bits), and a Remaining Length field encoded with variable-length encoding (1 to 4 bytes).

| Control Packet | Type Value | Direction |
|---|---|---|
| CONNECT | 1 | Client → Broker |
| CONNACK | 2 | Broker → Client |
| PUBLISH | 3 | Bidirectional |
| PUBACK | 4 | Ack for QoS 1 |
| PUBREC / PUBREL / PUBCOMP | 5 / 6 / 7 | Four-step handshake for QoS 2 |
| SUBSCRIBE / SUBACK | 8 / 9 | Client → Broker / Response |
| PINGREQ / PINGRESP | 12 / 13 | Keep-alive |
| DISCONNECT | 14 | Client → Broker (clean close) |

**QoS 0 — At most once**: Client sends `PUBLISH` once. No `PUBACK`. Message may be lost. Used for non-critical high-frequency sensor data (e.g., light intensity).

**QoS 1 — At least once**: Client sends `PUBLISH`, waits for `PUBACK`. If no ack within timeout, retransmit (DUP flag set). Duplicate delivery possible. Used for control commands.

**QoS 2 — Exactly once**: Four-step handshake — `PUBLISH` → `PUBREC` → `PUBREL` → `PUBCOMP`. Guarantees no duplicates. Highest overhead, used for billing or safety-critical messages.

**(b) JSON Schema and Topic Hierarchy (7 marks):**

**Topic Hierarchy** (3 marks):
```
ktu/home/livingroom/sensor/temperature
ktu/home/livingroom/sensor/humidity
ktu/home/livingroom/sensor/light
ktu/home/livingroom/actuator/fan/cmd
ktu/home/livingroom/actuator/bulb/cmd
```

**Telemetry JSON Payload** (2 marks) — published by ESP8266, received by app:
```json
{
  "deviceId": "ESP32_LR_01",
  "timestamp": 1716120000,
  "readings": {
    "temperature": 28.5,
    "humidity": 65.2,
    "light": 420
  }
}
```

**Command JSON Payload** (2 marks) — published by app, received by ESP8266:
```json
{
  "deviceId": "ESP32_LR_01",
  "command": "ON",
  "issuedBy": "user_mobile_app",
  "timestamp": 1716120050
}
```

The app would subscribe to `ktu/home/livingroom/sensor/+` (3 marks for the wildcard usage) and publish to the actuator command topics on button press.

