### 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Pitfalls — Where Students Lose Marks**
> 1. **Confusing QoS 0 and QoS 1**: Many students write "QoS 0 means the message is sent reliably" — this is WRONG. QoS 0 is fire-and-forget with no reliability guarantee. QoS 1 guarantees **at least** once delivery (possibly duplicated). QoS 2 guarantees **exactly** once.
> 2. **Forgetting the main-thread rule**: Writing `tempText.setText(...)` directly inside `messageArrived()` will crash the app on Android API 28+. You MUST wrap the UI update in `runOnUiThread()` or use `Handler(Looper.getMainLooper()).post()`.
> 3. **Using HTTP instead of MQTT**: A surprising number of submissions use `HttpURLConnection` and a REST API. The KTU syllabus explicitly mandates **MQTT** for the IoT lab. HTTP polling wastes battery and does not push.
> 4. **Missing `usesCleartextTraffic`**: On Android 9 (API 28) and above, plain `tcp://` connections to port 1883 are blocked by default. You must add `android:usesCleartextTraffic="true"` to the `<application>` tag or your app will silently fail to connect.
> 5. **Hardcoding the Client ID**: Using a static string like `"my_app"` as the Client ID will cause the broker to reject the second instance (duplicate ID). Always use `"KTU_" + System.currentTimeMillis()` or `UUID.randomUUID().toString()`.
> 6. **Forgetting to unsubscribe on `onDestroy()`**: Failing to call `mqttClient.disconnect()` in `onDestroy()` causes a **resource leak** and triggers the broker's Last Will and Testament (LWT) — the broker thinks the client crashed.

